# Create a list of numerical columns individually
numerical_columns = ['age', 'website_visits', 'time_spent_on_website', 'page_views_per_visit']

# Define colors for plots
boxplot_color = 'skyblue'
hist_color = 'lightcoral'
quartile_line_color = 'darkgreen'

# Iterate over numerical columns
for col in data[numerical_columns]: # Iterating over all the individual columns that are listed above

    # Create a new figure with two subplots
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6)) # setting the visuals siz

    # --- Boxplot ---
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)  # First subplot for boxplot
    sns.boxplot(data=data[col], color=boxplot_color, flierprops=dict(markerfacecolor='red', marker='D')) # Boxplot with red dots for outliers
    plt.title(f'Boxplot of {col}') # Title for the boxplot
    plt.ylabel(col) # Y-axis label

    # --- Histogram with KDE and Quartiles ---
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)  # Second subplot for histogram
    sns.histplot(data=data[col], kde=True, color=hist_color) # Histogram with KDE overlay
    plt.title(f'Distribution of {col}') # Title for the histogram
    plt.xlabel(col) # X-axis label
    plt.ylabel('Frequency') # Y-axis label

    # Add quartile lines
    q1, q3 = data[col].quantile([0.25, 0.75]) # Calculate quartiles
    plt.axvline(q1, color=quartile_line_color, linestyle='--', label=f'Q1 = {q1:.2f}') # Plot the first quartile line
    plt.axvline(q3, color=quartile_line_color, linestyle='--', label=f'Q3 = {q3:.2f}') # Plot the third quartile line
    plt.legend() # Add legend

    plt.tight_layout() # Adjust subplot spacing
    plt.show() # Display the plots

Interpretation of the above tables:

1.Websites per Visit The boxplot and distribution plot for websites per visit reveal: The median number of websites visited per session is approximately 2 to 3

The distribution is right-skewed, indicating that most visits involve a small number of websites, but some visits include a much larger number

The boxplot shows several outliers, with some visits involving 10 or more websites

2.Time Spent on Website The boxplot and distribution plot for time spent on websites show: The median time spent on a website is around 50 seconds . The distribution is heavily right-skewed, suggesting that while most website visits are relatively short, there are instances of much longer visits . There are numerous outliers in the boxplot, with some visits lasting over 300 minutes (5 hours) . Key Insights Browsing Behavior: Most users tend to visit only a few websites per session, typically 2 to 3. This suggests that users often have specific goals or interests when browsing. Visit Duration: The majority of website visits are brief, lasting less than a minute. This could indicate that users quickly find the information they need or decide if a site is relevant to their interests. Variability: Both metrics show considerable variability and notable outliers. This highlights the diverse range of user behaviors, from quick, focused visits to more extensive browsing sessions. User Engagement: The presence of outliers in both metrics suggests that some users engage in more in-depth browsing, either by visiting many websites or spending extended time on certain sites.

f, (ax_box, ax_hist) = plt.subplots(2, sharex=True, gridspec_kw={'height_ratios': (.15, .85)}, figsize=(10, 6))

# Set the visual style of the plots to 'darkgrid', which provides a dark background with grid lines
sns.set_style("darkgrid")

# Create a box plot on the first subplot (ax_box)
# The box plot shows the distribution of 'Customer_Age' and highlights the median, quartiles, and potential outliers
sns.boxplot(data=data, x="age", ax=ax_box)

# Create a histogram with a kernel density estimate (KDE) overlay on the second subplot (ax_hist)
# The histogram shows the frequency distribution of 'Customer_Age'
# The KDE provides a smoothed line that represents the probability density function
sns.histplot(data=data, x="age", kde=True, ax=ax_hist)

# Remove the x-axis label from the box plot (ax_box) to avoid duplication since the histogram (ax_hist) will have the same label
ax_box.set(xlabel='')

# Optionally, you can also set a title or y-axis labels if needed
ax_box.set_title('Customer Age Distribution')
ax_hist.set_ylabel('Frequency')

# Display the combined plots
plt.show()

Density Curve: The smooth line over the histogram represents the estimated probability density function, highlighting the distribution's shape. The outliers?

In [ ]:
# Select only the numeric columns (float64 and int64 types) from the DataFrame 'data'
numeric_data = data.select_dtypes(include=['float64', 'int64'])

# Calculate the first quartile (Q1) for each numeric column
# Q1 represents the 25th percentile, which is the value below which 25% of the data falls
Q1 = numeric_data.quantile(0.25)

# Calculate the third quartile (Q3) for each numeric column
# Q3 represents the 75th percentile, which is the value below which 75% of the data falls
Q3 = numeric_data.quantile(0.75)

# Compute the Interquartile Range (IQR) for each numeric column
# IQR is the range between the first quartile (Q1) and the third quartile (Q3), capturing the middle 50% of the data
IQR = Q3 - Q1

# Determine the lower bound for outliers for each numeric column
# This is calculated as Q1 minus 1.5 times the IQR, marking the threshold below which data points are considered outliers
lower = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR

# Determine the upper bound for outliers for each numeric column
# This is calculated as Q3 plus 1.5 times the IQR, marking the threshold above which data points are considered outliers
upper = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
In [ ]:
# Calculate Percentage of Outliers in Numerical Columns

(
    # Identify values outside the specified bounds
    (data.select_dtypes(include=["float64", "int64"]) < lower)  # Values below the lower bound
    | (data.select_dtypes(include=["float64", "int64"]) > upper)  # Values above the upper bound
# Sum the number of True values (outliers) per column, Divide by the total number of rows in the DataFrame, and Multiply by 100 to express as a percentage
).sum() / len(data) * 100

Splitting the data into 70% train and 30% test set

Some classification problems can exhibit a large imbalance in the distribution of the target classes: for instance there could be several times more negative samples than positive samples. In such cases it is recommended to use the stratified sampling technique to ensure that relative class frequencies are approximately preserved in each train and validation fold.

In [ ]:
# Perform the Split
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    X,               # The feature matrix (all your predictor variables)
    y,               # The target variable (the thing you're trying to predict)
    test_size=0.3,   # Proportion of the data to include in the test split (30% in this case)
    random_state=1,  # Seed for the random number generator (ensures reproducibility)
    stratify=y       # Split data in a way that maintains the same proportion of classes in both sets
)

        height = p.get_height() # Get the height (count) of the bar

        plt.gca().annotate(f'{height}',
                        (p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2., height),  # Position the text above the center of the bar
                        ha='center', va='center',                   # Horizontal and vertical alignment
                        xytext=(0, 10), textcoords='offset points')  # Adjust text position slightly above the bar
    plt.title(i) # Add a title to the plot
    plt.xticks(rotation=60) # Rotate x-axis labels to improve readability
    plt.ylabel("Count of Records") # Set the y-axis label
    plt.show() # Display the plot

Define a function named 'status_score' to evaluate the performance of a classification model

In [ ]:
# This function takes two parameters: 'actual' (true labels) and 'predicted' (model predictions)
def status_score(actual, predicted):
    # Print the classification report showing precision, recall, f1-score, and support for each class
    print(classification_report(actual, predicted))

    # Compute the confusion matrix to visualize the performance of the classification model
    cm = confusion_matrix(actual, predicted)

    # Set the size of the figure for the confusion matrix heatmap
    plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))

    # Create a heatmap to display the confusion matrix with annotations
    # 'annot=True' displays the values in each cell of the heatmap
    # 'fmt=".2f"' formats the annotations to 2 decimal places
    # 'xticklabels' and 'yticklabels' label the axes with class names for clarity
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='.2f', xticklabels=['Not enrolled', 'Enrolled'], yticklabels=['Not enrolled', 'Enrolled'])

    # Label the y-axis as 'Actual' to indicate the true labels
    plt.ylabel('Actual')

    # Label the x-axis as 'Predicted' to indicate the model's predictions
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')

    # Display the plot with the confusion matrix heatmap
    plt.show()

The coefficients of the logistic regression model give us the log of odds, which is hard to interpret in the real world. We can convert the log of odds into real odds by taking its exponential.

first_interaction_Website (1.57196): Users whose first interaction was through the website are 1.57 times more likely to enrol compared to those who didn't. referral_Yes (1.24747): Being referred increases the odds of being enrolled by about 25%. time_spent_on_website (1.00047): For each unit increase in time spent on the website, the odds of being enrolled increase very slightly (by 0.047%). website_visits (0.96340): Each additional website visit slightly decreases the odds of being enrolled by about 3.7%. age (0.95448): As age increases, the odds of of being enrolled decrease slightly (by about 4.5% per unit increase in age). page_views_per_visit (0.93260): More page views per visit are associated with slightly lower odds of being enrolled . digital_media_Yes (0.92573): Exposure to digital media slightly decreases the odds of of being enrolled . last_activity_Website Activity (0.90941): If the last activity was website-related, the odds of being enrolled are slightly lower. print_media_type2_Yes and print_media_type1_Yes (0.85772 and 0.83666): Exposure to these types of print media is associated with lower odds of being enrolled . educational_channels_Yes (0.78464): Engagement with educational channels is associated with lower odds of being enrolled . current_occupation_Unemployed (0.65345): Unemployed individuals have lower odds of being enrolled compared to the reference group. profile_completed_Low (0.65101): Users with low profile completion have lower odds of being enrolled . last_activity_Phone Activity (0.35917): If the last activity was phone-related, the odds of of being enrolled are significantly lower. profile_completed_Medium (0.32465): Users with medium profile completion have even lower odds than those with low completion. current_occupation_Student (0.10796): Students have significantly lower odds of being enrolled compared to the reference group. Second Image: Precision and Recall: The precision and recall vary more significantly across threshold values. Precision generally increases as the threshold increases, while recall decreases. # Evaluate SVM (RBF Kernel) Model and Plot Precision-Recall Curve

# Initialize and Fit SVM with RBF Kernel
svm_rbf = SVC(
    kernel='rbf',       # Use the Radial Basis Function (RBF) kernel for non-linear data
    probability=True   # Enable probability estimates for calculating precision and recall
)
svm_rbf.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train) # Train the SVM model on the scaled training data.
# The RBF kernel allows the model to capture non-linear decision boundaries, making it more flexible than a linear SVM.

# Calculate Prediction Probabilities
y_scores_svm = svm_rbf.predict_proba(X_train_scaled)
# This calculates the probability for each sample in the training set of belonging to each class .
# `y_scores_svm[:, 1]` specifically extracts the probability of being in the positive class (either enrolled or not).

# Calculate Precision, Recall, and Thresholds for Precision-Recall Curve
precisions_svm, recalls_svm, thresholds_svm = precision_recall_curve(
    y_train,          # True labels (ground truth)
    y_scores_svm[:, 1] # Predicted probabilities for the positive class
)

# Plot the Precision-Recall Curve
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 7))
plt.plot(thresholds_svm, precisions_svm[:-1], 'b--', label='Precision')  # Blue dashed line for precision
plt.plot(thresholds_svm, recalls_svm[:-1], 'g--', label='Recall')        # Green dashed line for recall

# Add labels and legend to the plot
plt.xlabel('Threshold')
plt.ylabel('Score')
plt.title('Precision-Recall Curve for SVM (RBF Kernel)')
plt.legend(loc='upper left')
plt.ylim([0, 1])  # Set y-axis limits to 0-1 (since precision and recall are proportions)

# Show the plot
plt.show()


# Find Threshold for Balanced Precision and Recall in SVM (RBF)

# Iterate through thresholds
for i in np.arange(len(thresholds_svm)):
    # Check if precision equals recall (with tolerance for floating-point errors)
    if abs(precisions_svm[i] - recalls_svm[i]) < 1e-5:
        # If found, print the threshold
        print(f"Threshold for balanced precision and recall: {thresholds_svm[i]:.3f}")

# It recursively creates nodes, choosing the best feature and threshold to split the data at each node until it reaches the maximum depth or some other stopping criterion.

# This line creates an instance of the RandomForestClassifier class from scikit-learn.
# The following hyperparameter is set during initialization:
    # random_state=1:
        # Sets a seed for the random number generator used within the Random Forest algorithm.
        # This ensures that the results are reproducible (you'll get the same forest structure if you run the code again).
        # This is important for consistency in model comparison and evaluation.
# Note that we are using default hyperparameters for other settings like `n_estimators` (number of trees). You might want to tune these hyperparameters later for better performance.

# Train the Random Forest Model
rf_estimator.fit(X_train, y_train)
# This line fits (trains) the Random Forest model on the training data.
# During training:
    # The algorithm builds multiple decision trees, each on a random subset of the data and features.
    # Each tree makes a prediction, and the final prediction for a new sample is based on the majority vote or average of the predictions from all the trees in the forest.
# This ensemble approach helps to reduce overfitting and improve the model's generalization performance.

# Evaluate Random Forest Model Performance on Training Set

# Predict Class Labels on Training Data
